attachments.title: Hundreds of Spotify credentials appear online – users report accounts hacked, emails changed
attachments.text:
A list containing hundreds of Spotify account credentials &ndash; including emails, usernames, passwords, account type and other details &ndash; has popped up&nbsp;on the website Pastebin, in what appears to be a possible security breach. After reaching out to a random sampling of the victims via email, we&rsquo;ve confirmed that these users&rsquo; Spotify accounts were compromised only days ago. However, Spotify says&nbsp;that it &ldquo;has not been hacked&rdquo; and its &ldquo;user records are secure.&rdquo;
It&rsquo;s unclear, then, where these particular&nbsp;account details were acquired, given that they are specific to Spotify, rather than a set of generic credentials that just happen to work on Spotify.
In addition to the email and login information, the Pastebin post also details the type of account (e.g. family, premium), when the subscription auto-renews, and the country where the account was created. The list of accounts is&nbsp;not limited to the U.S., but includes&nbsp;a number of users from all over the world.

Spotify has dealt with security incidents in the past, so one&nbsp;can&rsquo;t immediately assume that a list of emails like this is related to a new data breach. It could have been that a list of previously compromised accounts is still circulating. And only one of the accounts we tried actually permitted a log in, which also left&nbsp;room for doubt about the recency of this particular incident.
But the victims we reached out to told us otherwise.
So far, over a half-dozen have responded, confirming that they did experience a Spotify account breach recently. They became aware of the breach in a number of ways &ndash; for example, one said he found songs added to his saved songs list that he hadn&rsquo;t&nbsp;added.
Another also found his account had been used by an unknown third party.
&ldquo;I suspected my account had been hacked last week as I saw &lsquo;recently played&rsquo; songs that I&rsquo;d never listened to, so I changed my password and logged out of all devices,&rdquo; the victim, who preferred to remain anonymous, told us.

Several others said they were kicked out of Spotify &ndash; one even in the middle of streaming music.
When trying to log back in, these users found that their account email had been changed to a new email address not belonging to them.
To resolve the matter, users said they&rsquo;ve&nbsp;had to work with Spotify customer service to get their account access restored.
In none of the reported cases so far did Spotify reach out to the victims immediately following the breach, nor were their passwords proactively&nbsp;reset for them on their behalf by Spotify.
This seems to contradict the statement a Spotify spokesperson provided us today when asked about this possible breach:
&ldquo;Spotify has not been hacked and our user records are secure. We monitor Pastebin and other sites regularly. When we find Spotify credentials, we first verify that they are authentic, and if they are, we immediately notify affected users to change their passwords.
But it could be that Spotify is still in the process of verifying the account credentials, which takes time.
According to many of the&nbsp;users we spoke to so far, this&nbsp;issue occurred last week. The Pastebin is dated April 23, however. (TechCrunch is declining to link to the Pastebin page to protect the victims.)

Some of the victims are only now&nbsp;dealing with the fallout. A couple&nbsp;said they received the email notification that their password had been reset on Sunday.
&ldquo;&hellip;I was definitely hacked and later tried googling &lsquo;Spotify hack news&rsquo; last night to no avail,&rdquo; one&nbsp;victim told us. &ldquo;I noticed it last night when I opened Spotify on my phone and saw someone was using my account somewhere else.&rdquo;
The unknown party reset their email address, deleted a playlist, saved music to their device, and started following a new playlist.
Others are&nbsp;still in the process of trying to prove to Spotify they are the legitimate account owner.
&ldquo;&hellip;The person was able to change my email address without a second verification, and now I&rsquo;m jumping through hoops to close my account,&rdquo; another told&nbsp;us.
&ldquo;I had to reach out to Spotify first, and it&rsquo;s still ongoing,&rdquo; a third&nbsp;said. &ldquo;They&rsquo;ve not been helpful, and I&rsquo;ve only succeeded in getting my account locked so far.&rdquo;
Because of Spotify&rsquo;s&nbsp;delay in resetting users&rsquo; passwords, many of the victims told us they&rsquo;ve had problems that extend beyond the streaming service.
Unfortunately, because people&nbsp;often re-use their passwords on other sites, several reported their other accounts have been hacked into as well, including their Facebook, Uber, Skype and even their bank account.
It&rsquo;s unclear why the unknown third-parties responsible for this incident&nbsp;would want to actually use the Spotify user log ins to play music&nbsp;&ndash; especially as that alerts the users to the breach. Typically, a hacker would want to simply collect then re-sell the credentials, which makes this particular incident odd.
More to come, as information becomes available.
